    = Michael Blieden\n |WrittenBy       = Alisha Cowan\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|11}}\n |Viewers         = 0.246<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-11-2019.html |title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.11.2019 |publisher=Showbuzz Daily |date=2019-09-12 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = Mild Sauce Meatballs\n |DirectedBy      = Michael Blieden\n |WrittenBy       = Will Miles\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|18}}\n |Viewers         = 0.210<ref name=\"showbuzzdaily1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-18-2019.html |title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.18.2019 |publisher=Showbuzz Daily |date=2019-09-19 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Litcoin\n |DirectedBy      = Michael Blieden\n |WrittenBy       = Michael Blieden\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|18}}\n |Viewers         = 0.199<ref name=\"showbuzzdaily1\"/>\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nOn October 17, 2017, it was announced that Comedy Central had ordered the pilot for ''South Side'' from creators Bashir Salahuddin and Diallo Riddle, writing alums from ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/comedy-central-new-series-the-other-two-south-side-chris-kelly-and-sarah-schneider-lorne-michaels-diallo-riddle-bashir-salahuddin-1202189836/|title=Comedy Central Orders 2 New Series From 'Saturday Night Live', 'Late Night' Alums|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2017-10-17|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|author=Megh Wright |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/05/south-side-comedy-central-show-trailer.html |title=Trailer: Comedy Central's Upcoming Show 'South Side' |publisher=Vulture.com |date=2019-05-16 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref> The two also serve as executive producers and co-stars. On May 16, 2019, it was announced that the series would premiere on July 24, 2019.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nShowrunners Salahuddin and Riddle stated that ''South Side'' was created to portray the South Side of Chicago where Bashir Salahuddin grew up and to show that \"[t]here is joy on the South Side and the many Chicagoans who made this show, both in front of and behind the camera, are eager to share that joy.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://thegrapevine.theroot.com/watch-comedy-centrals-south-side-highlights-the-hope-a-1834809287|title=Watch: Comedy Central's South Side Highlights the 'Hope and Love' of Chicago in Debut Trailer|last=Stidhum|first=Tonja Ren\u00e9e|website=The Grapevine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> The show is set in [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] and features local actors and production members from Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/south-side-trailer-comedy-central-series-1202555304/|title=Comedy Central's 'South Side': Meet The Neighborhood \u2013 Trailer|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-02-12|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nSultan Salahuddin, cast in the lead role of Simon, is the brother of show creator Bashir Salahuddin. Bashir's wife, Chandra Russell, portrays the role of Sergeant Turner. Sultan Salahuddin's co-lead, Kareme Young, is the real-life twin brother of cast member Quincy Young, who also plays his brother in the show.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/south-side-comedy-central-review-bashir-salahuddin-diallo-riddle-interview|title=Comedy Central's South Side Is a Raucous Summer Must-Watch|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> Other cast members and guest stars include Chicago natives [[Lil Rel Howery]], Nathaniel \u201cEarthquake\u201d Stroman, [[LisaRaye McCoy]], and [[Kel Mitchell]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Release ===\nSouth Side premiered on July 24, 2019. On August 28, 2019, Comedy Central renewed the series for a 10-episode second season.<ref name=\"S2Renewal\" /> \n\n==Reception==\n''South Side'' received positive critical reception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/23/20706709/south-side-review-comedy-central-sitcom-show-richard-roeper|title='South Side' sitcom so funny, so smart, that 10 episodes aren't enough|last=Roeper|first=Richard|date=2019-07-23|website=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> The first season of the show has a score of 79/100 on review aggregator Metacritic, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=South Side|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/south-side|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Writing for ''Vanity Fair'', Laura Bradley stated: \"The writers worked to imbue the series with a diverse cast of characters whose values, socioeconomic status, and ambitions varied widely...the thing all of the show\u2019s main characters have in common is their drive.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Tambay Obenson wrote in a review for [[IndieWire]], \"The creators and cast know this world intimately, and instead of turning their camera on the usual crime and poverty, they find the humor that exists within the mayhem.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/south-side-review-comedy-central-1202158751/|title='South Side' Review: Comedy Central's New Series Humanizes an Oft-Derided Community|last=Obenson|first=Tambay|last2=Obenson|first2=Tambay|date=2019-07-23|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n== Other media ==\nOn September 4, 2019, Comedy Central and [[WBEZ|WBEZ Chicago]] launched ''South Side Stories'', a groundbreaking podcast collaboration between a public media organization and a cable television partner that celebrates the real-life people and places that inspired the hit scripted comedy series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://press.cc.com/series/south-side/press-releases|title=South Side {{!}} Press Releases|website=Comedy Central Press|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cc.com/shows/southside Official website]\n*''[[imdbtitle:9272514|South Side]]'' on IMDb\n\n{{Comedy Central programming}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American black television series]]\n[[Category:Comedy Central original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "Citrivescence", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther media:removed non-neutral language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Side_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen", "text_new": "{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image coat of arms     = Blason Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen.svg\n|image                  = Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen - Saint-Vincent-de-Paul.JPG\n|caption                = The church in Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen\n|image flag             = \n|image flag size        = \n|flag legend            = \n|city motto             = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|49.4092|1.09|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|INSEE                  = 76681\n|arrondissement         = [[Arrondissement of Rouen|Rouen]]\n|canton                 = [[Canton of Le Petit-Quevilly|Le Petit-Quevilly]], [[Canton of Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen|Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen]]\n|intercommunality       = [[M\u00e9tropole Rouen Normandie]]\n|mayor                  = Luce Pane\n|party                  = [[Socialist Party (France)|PS]]\n|term                   = 2014 - 2020\n|area km2               = 7.44\n|area footnotes         = \n|population             = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date        = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n|population ranking     = [[List of communes in France with over 20,000 inhabitants|283rd in France]]\n|website                = {{url|https://www.sotteville-les-rouen.fr/}}\n}}\n'''Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Seine-Maritime]] [[Departments of France|department]] in the [[Normandy]] region in northern [[France]].\n\n==Geography==\nIt is the largest suburb of the city of [[Rouen]] and adjacent to it, some {{convert|2|mi|km}} south of the centre of [[Rouen]] at the junction of the D94 and the D18 roads.\n\n==Heraldry==\n{{Blazon-arms\n|img1=Blason Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen.svg\n|legend1=Arms of Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen\n|text=The arms of Sotteville-l\u00e8s-Rouen are [[blazon]]ed :<br />''Per bend 1: Azure, a beehive within 7 bees in orle Or; 2: Vert, a Budicom locomotive Or; a bend gules fimbriated argent, and on a chief gules, a leopard Or armed and langued azure.''\n}}\n\n== Transportation ==\nThe [[Tramway de Rouen|''m\u00e9tro'']] connects the commune with [[Rouen]] and [[Saint-\u00c9tienne-du-Rouvray]].\n\nThe commune used to be a [[railway town]] in the days of the [[old Rouen tramway]].\n\n== Population ==\n{| align=\"center\" rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"border: 1px solid #999; border-right: 2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background: #f3fff3\"\n|+ style=\"font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em\"|Population history\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd\"\n!  1962 !! 1968 !! 1975 !! 1982 !! 1990 !! 1999 !! 2006\n|-\n| align=center| 33,443 || align=center| 34,495 || align=center| 31,659 || align=center| 30,558 || align=center| 29,544|| align=center| 29,553|| align=center| 30,076\n|-\n| colspan=7 align=center| <small>Starting in 1962: Population without duplicates</small>\n|}\n\n== Places of interest ==\n* The three churches of Notre-Dame, St. Vincent and Notre-Dame, all dating from the twentieth century.\n\n== People ==\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Alix]] (1907\u20131966), choral conductor and composer\n* [[Jacques Anquetil]] (1934\u20131987), [[racing cyclist]], started his career here with AC Sotteville.\n* [[Anny Duperey]] (1947-), comedian, lives here.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Communes of the Seine-Maritime department]]\n\n== References ==\n*[http://www.insee.fr/en/home/home_page.asp INSEE]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* L. Leroy, D. Andrieu et J.-F. Glabik, Sotteville, une vie, \u00e9d. Maison pour Tous, 1989 ; 1991 {{ISBN|2-909094-00-6}}\n* Guy Pessiot, Histoire de l\u2019agglom\u00e9ration rouennaise : la rive gauche, \u00e9d. du P\u2019tit Normand, 1990 {{ISBN|978-2-906258-22-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{