{"title_page": "You're Breaking My Heart", "text_new": "{{for|the Harry Nilsson song|You're Breakin' My Heart}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = You're Breaking My Heart\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1948\n| writer    = Pat Genaro<br />[[Sunny Skylar]]<br />[[Ruggero Leoncavallo]]\n| composer  =\n| lyricist  =\n}}\n\"'''You're Breaking My Heart'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]]. The song was published in [[1948 in music|1948]]. Though credited to [[Pat Genaro]] and [[Sunny Skylar]], (With acknowledgements to the owners of the copyright in \"Tis the Day\") the song is an English version of the famous Italian song '[[Mattinata (Leoncavallo)|Mattinata]]' written by [[Ruggero Leoncavallo]] in the beginning of 20th century (that song had lapsed into the public domain in the United States by the time this English song was set to its tune).\n\n==Popular recordings ==\nPopular versions on the charts in [[1949 in music|1949]] included recordings by [[Vic Damone]], [[The Ink Spots]], [[Buddy Clark]], and [[Jan Garber]].\n\nThe [[Vic Damone]] recording was released by [[Mercury Records]] as catalog number 5271. The flip side was \"[[Four Winds and Seven Seas]].\" The recording first entered the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] chart on June 10, 1949, lasting 26 weeks and peaking at position #1.<ref name=Whitburn>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Top Pop Records 1940-1955|date=1973|publisher=Record Research}}</ref>\n\n[[The Ink Spots]]' recording featuring [[Bill Kenny (singer)|Bill Kenny]] (June 27, 1949) was released by [[Decca Records]] as catalog number 24693. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on August 12, 1949, lasting 14 weeks and peaking at position #9.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe [[Buddy Clark]] recording was recorded on June 21, 1949, and released by [[Columbia Records]] as catalog number 38546. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on September 2, 1949, lasting 13 weeks and peaking at position #9.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe [[Jan Garber]] recording was released by [[Capitol Records]] as catalog number 719 with \"Now That I Need You\" on the flip side. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on September 23, 1949, lasting two weeks and peaking at position #26.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe song was also recorded by [[Ralph Flanagan]] and his orchestra, with vocalist [[Harry Prime]], on August 18, 1949, and released by the [[Bluebird Records]] subsidiary of [[RCA Victor Records]] as catalog number 30-0001.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\n[[Keely Smith]]'s remake made the British Top 20 in 1965.\n\n[[Eddie Fisher (singer)|Eddie Fisher]] also notably sang this song on a number of early 1950s television programs, often presided over by [[Eddie Cantor]], and during a number of live performances, but never actually recorded it.  However several of those versions can be heard on music video platforms.  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Ink Spots}}\n{{Vic Damone}}\n\n[[Category:Number-one singles in the United States]]\n[[Category:1948 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sunny Skylar]]\n[[Category:Vic Damone songs]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Harry Nilsson song|You're Breakin' My Heart}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name      = You're Breaking My Heart\n| cover     =\n| alt       =\n| type      =\n| written   =\n| published = 1948\n| writer    = Pat Genaro<br />[[Sunny Skylar]]<br />[[Ruggero Leoncavallo]]\n| composer  =\n| lyricist  =\n}}\n\"'''You're Breaking My Heart'''\" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]]. The song was published in [[1948 in music|1948]]. Though credited to [[Pat Genaro]] and [[Sunny Skylar]], (With acknowledgements to the owners of the copyright in \"Tis the Day\") the song is an English version of the famous Italian song '[[Mattinata (Leoncavallo)|Mattinata]]' written by [[Ruggero Leoncavallo]] in the beginning of 20th century (that song had lapsed into the public domain in the United States by the time this English song was set to its tune).\n\n==Popular recordings ==\nPopular versions on the charts in [[1949 in music|1949]] included recordings by [[Vic Damone]], [[The Ink Spots]], [[Buddy Clark]], and [[Jan Garber]].\n\nThe [[Vic Damone]] recording was released by [[Mercury Records]] as catalog number 5271. The flip side was \"[[Four Winds and Seven Seas]].\" The recording first entered the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] chart on June 10, 1949, lasting 26 weeks and peaking at position #1.<ref name=Whitburn>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Top Pop Records 1940-1955|date=1973|publisher=Record Research}}</ref>\n\n[[The Ink Spots]]' recording featuring [[Bill Kenny (singer)|Bill Kenny]] (June 27, 1949) was released by [[Decca Records]] as catalog number 24693. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on August 12, 1949, lasting 14 weeks and peaking at position #9.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe [[Buddy Clark]] recording was recorded on June 21, 1949, and released by [[Columbia Records]] as catalog number 38546. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on September 2, 1949, lasting 13 weeks and peaking at position #9.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe [[Jan Garber]] recording was released by [[Capitol Records]] as catalog number 719 with \"Now That I Need You\" on the flip side. The recording first entered the ''Billboard'' chart on September 23, 1949, lasting two weeks and peaking at position #26.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\nThe song was also recorded by [[Ralph Flanagan]] and his orchestra, with vocalist [[Harry Prime]], on August 18, 1949, and released by the [[Bluebird Records]] subsidiary of [[RCA Victor Records]] as catalog number 30-0001.<ref name=Whitburn/>\n\n[[Keely Smith]]'s remake made the British Top 20 in 1965.\n\n[[Eddie Fisher]] also notably sang this song on a number of early 1950s television programs, often presided over by [[Eddie Cantor]], and during a number of live performances, but never actually recorded it.  However several of those versions can be heard on music video platforms.  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Ink Spots}}\n{{Vic Damone}}\n\n[[Category:Number-one singles in the United States]]\n[[Category:1948 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sunny Skylar]]\n[[Category:Vic Damone songs]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toEdward Fisher(link changed toEddie Fisher (singer)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You%27re_Breaking_My_Heart"}
{"title_page": "Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n| post = Chairman\n| body = the<br />Workers' Party of Korea\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|ko|\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5}}}}\n| flag = Flag of the Workers' Party of Korea.svg\n| flagsize = 120px\n| flagcaption = Flag of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| insignia = WPK symbol.svg\n| insigniacaption = Logo of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| department = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| image = Kim and Trump standing next to each other (cropped).jpg\n| incumbent = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n| incumbentsince = 9 May 2016\n| type = [[Party leader]]\n| residence = [[Forbidden City (Pyongyang)|Forbidden City]]\n| seat = [[Pyongyang]]\n| nominator = [[National meetings of the Workers' Party of Korea|WPK Congress]]\n| termlength = No fixed term\n| constituting_instrument = [[Charter of the Workers' Party of Korea|WPK Charter]]\n| inaugural = [[Kim Tu-bong]]\n| appointer = WPK Congress\n| deputy = [[Executive Policy Bureau of the Workers' Party of Korea|Vice Chairman]]\n| formation = 28 August 1946\n| imagesize = 165px\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul = \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5\n| hanja = \u671d\u9bae\u52de\u52d5\u9ee8 \u59d4\u54e1\u9577\n| mr = Chos\u014fn Rodongdang Wiwonjang\n| rr = Joseon Rodongdang Wiwonjang\n| context = north}}The '''Chairman of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5) is the head of the [[Workers' Party of Korea|Workers\u2019 Party of Korea]], the ruling political party in [[North Korea]].\n\nThe [[Charter of the Workers' Party of Korea|Charter of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea]] states the Chairman of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea is the supreme leader of the party. The Party Congress nominates and elects the WPK Chairman. The Party Conference is also able to nominate and elect the WPK Chairman. The WPK Chairman serves as the ex officio Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Military Commission of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea]]. In practice, the WPK Chairman is also a member of the [[Presidium of the Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Presidium]] of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Political Bureau]] and the head of the [[Executive Policy Bureau of the Workers' Party of Korea|Executive Policy Bureau]].\n\nThe current Chairman of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea is [[Kim Jong-un]], who took office on 9 May 2016.\n\n== History ==\nThe position was first established as the '''Chief Secretary of the North Korea Bureau of the [[Communist Party of Korea]]''' (Korean: \uc870\uc120\uacf5\uc0b0\ub2f9 \ubd81\uc870\uc120\ubd84\uad6d \ucc45\uc784\ube44\uc11c) on 13 October 1945 during the conference of Communist Party of Korea members in northern Korea. Kim Yong-bom was elected as the first chief secretary. He was succeeded by [[Kim Il-sung]], who was elected as chief secretary on 18 December 1945 at the third enlarged executive committee meeting of the North Korea Bureau of the Communist Party of Korea.\n\nOn 28 August 1946, the North Korean Bureau of the Communist Party of Korea and the [[New People's Party of Korea|New People\u2019s Party of Korea]] were merged to form the [[Workers' Party of North Korea|Workers\u2019 Party of North Korea]] during its [[1st Congress of the Workers' Party of North Korea|1st Congress]]. The position of '''Chairman of the Central Committee of the Workers\u2019 Party of North Korea''' (Korean: \ubd81\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc911\uc559\uc704\uc6d0\ud68c \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5) was also created to lead the new party. [[Kim Tu-bong]], the chairman of the New People\u2019s Party of Korea, was elected as the chairman and was re-elected in March 1948 during the [[2nd Congress of the Workers' Party of North Korea|2nd Congress]].\n\nOn 30 June 1949, the Workers\u2019 Party of North Korea and the [[Workers' Party of South Korea|Workers\u2019 Party of South Korea]] merged to form the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea. The position of '''Chairman of the Central Committee of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' (Korean: \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc911\uc559\uc704\uc6d0\ud68c \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5) was also created. Kim Il-sung, who was a vice chairman of the WPNK central committee, was elected as chairman and was re-elected in April 1956 during the [[3rd Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|3rd WPK Congress]] and in September 1961 during the [[4th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|4th WPK Congress]].\n\nOn 12 October 1966, the position of '''General Secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' (Korean: \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc911\uc559\uc704\uc6d0\ud68c \ucd1d\ube44\uc11c) was created at the 14th plenary meeting of the 4th WPK Central Committee. Kim Il-sung was elected by the meeting as general secretary and was re-elected in November 1970 at the [[5th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|5th WPK Congress]] and in October 1980 at the [[6th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|6th WPK Congress]].\n\nKim Il-sung held the position of general secretary until [[Death and state funeral of Kim Il-sung|his death on 8 July 1994]]. Following this, the post was left vacant until 1997.\n\nFrom late September until early October 1997, conferences of various WPK conferences were held to recommend the election of [[Kim Jong-il]] as general secretary. Kim Jong-il is the designated successor of Kim Il-sung. At that point, Kim Jong-il held the party positions of Political Bureau Presidium member and WPK central committee secretary.\n\nOn 8 October 1997, the Central Committee and the Central Military Commission issued a special communique stating that Kim Jong-il was elected to the position of '''General Secretary of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' (Korean: \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \ucd1d\ube44\uc11c).\n\nOn 28 September 2010, Kim Jong-il was re-elected as WPK general secretary at the 3rd WPK Conference. The conference also amended the Charter of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea to state that the WPK general secretary is the ex officio Chairman of the Central Military Commission of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea.\n\n[[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Kim Jong-il died on 17 December 2011]] and the position of general secretary was left vacant.\n\nThe WPK held its 4th Conference on 11 April 2012. It declared Kim Jong-il as the '''eternal General Secretary of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' (Korean: \uc601\uc6d0\ud55c \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \ucd1d\ube44\uc11c). The WPK Charter was revised to create the '''First Secretary of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea''' (Korean: \uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc81c1\ube44\uc11c) as the new highest party position.\n\nKim Jong-un was elected as first secretary on 11 April 2012 during the 4th WPK Conference. Kim Jong-un is the designated successor of Kim Jong-il. Prior to his election as WPK first secretary, Kim Jong-un held the party positions of Central Military Commission vice chairman and Central Committee member.\n\nOn 9 May 2016, the [[7th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|7th WPK Congress]] created the Chairman of the Workers\u2019 Party of Korea as the new highest party position. Kim Jong-un was elected by the congress as the WPK chairman.{{Politics of North Korea}}\n\n==Office holders==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:70%; border:1px #AAAAFF solid\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |'''Chief Secretary of the North Korea Bureau of the Communist Party of Korea'''<br><small>\uc870\uc120\uacf5\uc0b0\ub2f9 \ubd81\uc870\uc120\ubd84\uad6d \ucc45\uc784\ube44\uc11c</small>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Chief Secretary\n! colspan=\"2\" |Term\n!Election\n|-\n|\n|'''<big>Kim Yong-bom</big>'''<br><span style=\"font-size:100%;\">\uae40\uc6a9\ubc94</span><br>1902&ndash;1947<br>\n| rowspan=\"1\" |13 October 1945\n| rowspan=\"1\" |18 December 1945\n| rowspan=\"1\" | -\n|-\n|[[File:Kim Il-sung in 1950.jpg|frameless|193x193px]]\n|'''<big>[[Kim Il-sung]]</big>'''<br><span style=\"font-size:100%;\">\uae40\uc77c\uc131</span><br>1912&ndash;1994\n[[File:Kim_Il_Sung_Signature.svg|100px]]<br>\n|18 December 1945\n|31 August 1946\n| -\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" |'''Chairman of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of North Korea'''<br><small>\ubd81\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc911\uc559\uc704\uc6d0\ud68c \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5</small>\n|- style=\"background:#cccccc\"\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Chairman\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Term\n!align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Election\n|- \n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |{{CSS image crop|Image = 28.08.1946 Labour Party North Korea.jpg|bSize = 1200|cWidth = 150|cHeight = 200|oTop = 420 |oLeft = 650}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''<big>[[Kim Tu-bong]]</big>'''<br><span style=\"font-size:100%;\">\uae40\ub450\ubd09</span><br>1889&ndash;1958<br>\n| rowspan=\"1\" |31 August 1946\n| rowspan=\"1\" |30 March 1948\n| rowspan=\"1\" |[[1st Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|1st<br>Central<br>Committee]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |30 March 1948\n| rowspan=\"1\" |30 June 1949\n| rowspan=\"1\" |[[2nd Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea|2nd<br>Central<br>Committee]]\n|-\n!colspan=5 | '''Chairman of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea'''<br><small>\uc870\uc120\ub85c\ub3d9\ub2f9 \uc911\uc559\uc704\uc6d0\ud68c \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5</small>\n|- style=\"background:#cccccc\"\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Chairman\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Term\n!align=\"center\" width=\"0\"|Election\n|- \n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[File:Kim Il-sung in 1950.jpg|frameless|193x193px]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |'''<big>[[Kim Il-sung]]</big>'''<br><span style=\"font-size:100%;\">\uae40\uc77c\uc131</span><br>1912&ndash;1994<br>[[File:Kim_Il_Sung_Signature.svg|100px]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" |30 June 1949\n| rowspan=\"1\" |29 April 1956\n| rowspan=\